132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST SPECIAL SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1598
H.P. 1056 House of Representatives, April 10, 2025
An Act to Provide Relocation Assistance to Victims of Domestic
Violence, Sexual Assault and Sex Trafficking
Reference to the Committee on Judiciary suggested and ordered printed.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative STOVER of Boothbay.
Cosponsored by Representatives: GRAMLICH of Old Orchard Beach, MEYER of Eliot,
PLUECKER of Warren, RANA of Bangor, SATO of Gorham, Senator: RENY of Lincoln.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 5 MRSA §3360, sub-§3-A is enacted to read:
3 3-A. Domestic violence crime. "Domestic violence crime" means domestic violence
4 assault, as described in Title 17-A, section 207-A; domestic violence aggravated assault,
5 as described in Title 17-A, section 208-D; domestic violence elevated aggravated assault,
6 as described in Title 17-A, section 208-E; domestic violence elevated aggravated assault
7 on a pregnant person, as described in Title 17-A, section 208-F; domestic violence criminal
8 threatening, as described in Title 17-A, section 209-A; domestic violence terrorizing, as
9 described in Title 17-A, section 210-B; domestic violence stalking, as described in Title
10 17-A, section 210-C; and domestic violence reckless conduct, as described in Title 17-A,
11 section 211-A.
12 Sec. 2. 5 MRSA §3360, sub-§7 is enacted to read:
13 7. Qualified counselor. "Qualified counselor" means a sexual assault counselor as
14 defined in Title 16, section 53-A, subsection 1, paragraph B and an advocate as defined in
15 Title 16, section 53-B, subsection 1, paragraph A.
16 Sec. 3. 5 MRSA §3360, sub-§8 is enacted to read:
17 8. Sexual assault or trafficking crime. "Sexual assault or trafficking crime" means
18 sexual assaults as described in Title 17-A, chapter 11 and aggravated sex trafficking or sex
19 trafficking as described in Title 17-A, sections 852 and 853, respectively.
20 Sec. 4. 5 MRSA §3360-E, sub-§6 is enacted to read:
21 6. Relocation assistance for victims of domestic violence, sexual assault or
22 trafficking crimes. Notwithstanding the compensation limits in subsections 1 and 3, if the
23 underlying crime is a domestic violence crime or a sexual assault or trafficking crime, the
24 board may award compensation for actual and unreimbursed relocation expenses in
25 accordance with the provisions of this subsection.
26 A. The board may award up to $3,000 to a victim, except that, if the victim is the victim
27 of one or more subsequent domestic violence crimes or sexual assault or trafficking
28 crimes, the board may award additional compensation as long as the lifetime total
29 compensation the victim receives under this subsection does not exceed $5,000.
30 B. Compensation may be awarded under this subsection only if:
31 (1) A qualified counselor certifies in writing that the victim had an urgent need to
32 relocate to escape an unsafe environment directly related to the domestic violence
33 crime or the sexual assault or trafficking crime and that the relocation was part of
34 a safety plan developed by the victim with a qualified counselor; or
35 (2) A prosecutor certifies in writing that the victim had an urgent need to relocate
36 due to the threat of future violence associated with an ongoing investigation and
37 criminal prosecution of the domestic violence crime or the sexual assault or
38 trafficking crime.
39 SUMMARY
4400 This bill provides that a victim of a domestic violence crime or a sexual assault or
4411 trafficking crime is eligible to receive up to $3,000 in compensation from the Victims'
Page 1 - 132LR2014(01)

412 Compensation Board for actual and unreimbursed relocation expenses to escape an unsafe
423 environment directly related to the underlying crime or to alleviate a threat of future
434 violence associated with the ongoing investigation and criminal prosecution of the
445 underlying crime. If the victim is the victim of one or more subsequent domestic violence
456 crimes or sexual assault or trafficking crimes, the board may award additional relocation
467 assistance as long as the total lifetime relocation assistance the victim receives from the
478 board does not exceed $5,000.
